  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT340-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">iravukkuṟi uṇarttiya tōḻikkuk kiḻatti maṟuttatu. </p>


        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">SHE refused the confidante, who announced night trysts. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT340">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> kāmaṅ kaṭaiyiṟ kātalarp paṭarntu</l>
          <l> nāmavarp pulampi ṉammō ṭāki</l>
          <l> yorupāṟ paṭutal cellā tāyiṭai</l>
          <l> yaḻuva niṉṟa valarvēy kaṇṭal</l>
          <l> kaḻipeyar maruṅki ṉolki yōtam</l>
          <l> peyartarap peyartan tāṅku</l>
          <l> varuntun tōḻiyava riruntaveṉ ṉeñcē.</l>


        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>At a time it set out for the lover, when desire increased,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">[and] was with us, when we lamented him,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">without [however] going to share one [single] fate, <note place="foot"> Meaning the heart does not choose between HER and the lover? T.V.G. explains the phrase as "not being stable on one side", but how to account for syntax and semantics?   </note></l>
          <l>my heart that was with him, <note place="foot"> What is the nuance conveyed by <term xml:lang="ta"> irunta </term> here? Is it a temporary stay, that is, he has been with her heart, but is no longer? Or rather the fear that it might be so? Both further variants are equally possible,<term xml:lang="ta"> arunta </term> ("my heart that had imbibed him") as well as the infinitive <term xml:lang="ta"> varunta </term>, with a different nuance: "my heart suffers, friend, for him to suffer." </note> is troubled, friend,</l>
          <l rend="indent">like the flood moving [just] to move [again] <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> peyar taru </term> has the nuance of involuntarity/inevitability of the movement, while the repetition is iterative. </note> </l>
          <l rend="indent">[and] becoming weak on the side where the backwaters stir</l>
          <l rend="indent2">with blossom-covered mangroves standing <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> niṉṟa </term>: why here the perfective aspect? Is it that the trees have found hold in the depth?     </note> in the depth.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
